TULAREMIA - USA (MARTHA'S VINEYARD, MASSACHUSETTS)
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Tularemia - Sweden, Finland 19950831.0779
Date: 31 Aug 2000 14:26:43 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: MSNBC, 31 Aug 2000 [edited

A rare bacterial infection usually found in rabbits and rodents [as well as
over 100 other mammalian species and numerous arthropods -DS has been
blamed for the death of one person and the infection of at least 9 others
on Martha's Vineyard since Jun 2000, according to health officials. A 43
year old male from Chilmark, died Saturday [26 Aug 2000 after he was
stricken with tularemia, according to Maia Gaillard, a Martha's Vineyard
Hospital spokeswoman. She said he was severely ill when he came to the
hospital, and later was transferred to Boston Medical Center, where he died.
All 9 of the other people known to have tularemia were successfully treated
with antibiotics and recovered, Roseanne Pawelec, spokeswoman for the state
Department of Public Health, told the Cape Cod Times. The disease is passed
from rabbits and rodents, such as squirrels, voles and muskrats, to humans
through dog tick bites. People can also catch the disease by eating or
coming in contact with an infected animal, contaminated water or soil [as
well as by inhalation, consumption of a contaminated animal, in laboratory
accidents, and (in some locations) bites of mosquitoes or deer flies -DS.
Deer ticks do not carry the disease. The infected people have been males
between the ages of 13 and 59, according to the Martha's Vineyard Gazette,
and most of the infected people have outdoor occupations such as
landscaping and construction work. The others mow their own lawns.
Tularemia comes on suddenly with symptoms that include swollen glands
[lymphadenopathy, a high fever, chills, fatigue, headache, a sore throat,
sore joints, chest discomfort, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhea and a dry
cough [ulcers, either with or without associated lymphadenopathy, and
ocular involvement, either with or without associated lymphadenopathy are
other common presentations. -Man. Ed. DS. Symptoms generally appear three
to five days after an exposure to the bacteria, although they can take as
long as 14 days to appear [actually up to 21 days and can appear after less
than a 3 day incubation period as well -DS. Pawelec said that generally
one to 3 people are diagnosed each year with the disease. "Ten confirmed
cases is unusual," Pawelec said. "The last time there was a death was a
woman from Duxbury in 1996." The last time there was an outbreak on the
Vineyard was in the 1970s, Gaillard said. Some health officials speculate
that wet weather this summer may have contributed to the sharp rise in
tularemia because the bacteria remain alive much longer in damp weather.
